&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]the Medical Schools Council and Dental Schools (WSC064)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Both organisations represent the interests and ambitions of UK medical and dental schools as they relate to the generation of national health, wealth and knowledge through biomedical research and the professions of medicine and dentistry. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This submission
[normal] includes contributions received from individual responses, UK medical and dental schools and the Equality Challenge Unit, Athena SWAN Medical and Dental Schools Advisory Group.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Difficulties related to working in STEM 
[normal]clinical and non-cl
[normal]inical 
[normal]academic careers are faced by both men and women. However, 
[normal]wider
[normal] issues affect the 
[normal]retention and progression of women
[normal] in academic STEM careers
[normal] for example, limited 
[normal]senior women role models
[normal], women often having a greater proportion of teaching/pastor
[normal]al student roles, limited opportunities for part-time/flexible working, 
[normal]and 
[normal]women taking on the major
[normal]ity of caring responsibilities. T
[normal]he cycle is self-perpetuating. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a 
[normal]gendered conception of merit in clinical and non-clinical academia
[normal], especially
[normal] one tha
[normal]t values a full-time/long-hours
[normal] uninterrupted career trajectory and research success. The achievements that women make are often unrecognised, as women are often too modest and do not market themselves enough, or reaching the same level of achievement either takes longer, or does not oc
[normal]cur to the same level, due to career breaks, work-life balance and return to work challenges.
[normal] [bold]Women Professors have increased by only 5% since 2004 (from 11% to 16%
[normal]1
[normal]), and more work is required to ensure gender balance at senior academic levels.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The drain
[normal] of women from academic medicine and dentistry represents a significant 
[normal]loss of talent and expertise to the HE and research sectors
[normal], to the detriment of research innovation and leadership. There is some evidence that the number and proportion of wome
[normal]n in s
[normal]enior roles is increasing
[normal] – however, this is o
[normal]c
[normal]curring very slowly and needs urgent attention.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Medical and dental school initiatives to support academic women are commended and should be sustained and expanded. Such initiatives support the goals and ambit
[normal]ions of the Athena SWAN charter for Women in Science, which UK medical and dental schools are working towards and several have achieved Silver or Bronze awards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Structured clinical academic training pathways e.g. NIHR should be protected and marketed as a
[normal]spirational.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a need to provide affordable, quality childcare. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The most recent data (2012) on
[normal] academic medicine 
[normal]and dentistry staffing levels shows that
[normal], as 
[normal]for 
[normal]other STEM subjects, there continues to be a small proportion of women 
[normal]Professors (16%), particularly when compared with Senior Lecturer/Readers (32% medicine, 39% dentistry) and Lecturers (44%). Yet HESA data show that 54% of medical students and 59% of dental students are women. Progression from Lecturer grade is a key chal
[normal]lenge for female academics.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The number and proportion of women at each academic grade has increased since 2004 (Figures 1 and 2), with women professors increasing by 5% since 2004 (from 11% to 16%). 
