[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Work-life balance: 
[normal]4.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An academic career is usually less well-defined than one in the NHS and is 
[normal]perceived to be more stressful, particularly in the early career stages. It demands a significant investment of time, includ
[normal]ing out-of-
[normal]program training, a
[normal]nd contracts may be short-term 
[normal]without clear progression routes. Success is dependent on factors such 
[normal]as research grant income or proof of outstanding contributions to education. Promotion prospects are less attractive, as it takes longer to achieve equal clinical status, and there are fewer opportunities e.g. for on-call or private work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Many staff exper
[normal]ience busy workloads, often involving heavy teaching and administrative duties, which reduces the time available for research within core hours, leading to a long-hours culture. Part-time or job-share opportunities do not necessarily fit with the cultural 
[normal]image of ‘total commitment to the academic agenda’, and women tend to apply for jobs that they perceive to offer a better work-life balance.
[normal] Moreover, it is difficult to maintain an active research programme
[normal] with external funding and high-
[normal]quality pub
[normal]licat
[normal]ions in a part-time or job-
[normal]share context for clinical or non-clinical academics.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are very few part-time opportunities, and virtually none at Clinical Academic Consultant level. Complex responsibilities in clinical, teaching and research roles – in a
[normal]ddition to family commitments
[normal] -
[normal] mean that even working full-time, women with clinical responsibilities tend to complete PhDs over 6+ years, or more if they have maternity leave. Women feel their career progression rates may be compromised unless they atten
[normal]d networking, conferences or national meetings.
[normal] Expectations have been increased with the impact of the 2014 REF.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The challenges of work-life balance in academia tend to be exacerbated for women with children or other caring commitments, who generally ta
[normal]ke on the majority of responsibilities.
[normal] As one medical school reported ‘More often than not, very successful men will have partners or wives that have less pressured work roles and are thus better able to support them. The reverse is rarely true.’ 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack
[normal] of confidence:
[normal]4.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women tend to wait until they meet all the criteria for promotion, whereas men tend to be more speculative in their applications. Consequently, women are less likely to submit themselves for consideration for promotion without encouragement
[normal] or mentoring. Evidence from the Advisory Committee on Clinical Excellence Awards
[normal] and medical/ dental schools internal records show that when women do apply, they are just as likely to be successful.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of opportunities:
[normal]4.3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Appointments and promotions pro
[normal]cesses are one of the four key barriers to a women’s progression.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Search committees frequently comprise predominantly men, who may only consider their networks and potential female candidates may not be identified. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A requirement to move institution for
[normal] career advancement may not fit with family commitments. Many early career researchers need to be geographically mobile, a disincentive, which inhibits continuity of employment rights.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Support for moving from PhD to post-doctoral posts is often inadequate
[normal], and often dependent on the PhD supervisor communicating events, opportunities and helping to access funds for future roles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a significant di
[normal]sparity in the number of women o
[normal]n fixed-term contracts with external rather than core funding compared 
[normal]to their male counterparts.
[normal]  The insecurity of fixed-term contracts, which often coincides with the timing of childbearing decisions, is another reason why women do not progress in their academic careers.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women can spend too much time on activities that benefit the 
[normal]s
[normal]chool, for example being an admissions/year tutor, with less time to focus on research or teaching activities that warrant promotion or progression.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Career breaks:
[normal]4.4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Career breaks in science acad
[normal]emia can have a severe long-term effect on a career than in other professions. It takes time to build up a research group and facilities, its associated funding and a line of research showing results. This
[normal],
[normal] and the fast-pace of research, means it can requi
[normal]re a great deal of effort for women to get back on track.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a lack of fellowship schemes for female academic clinicians returning to pursue an academic career after having a family, 
[normal]although 
[normal]some do exist for non-clinicians (e.g. Daphne Jackson an
[normal]d Dorothy Hodgkin schemes).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unconscious bias:
[normal]4.5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Social assumptions and norms around gender can have a huge impact. The assumed identity of an academic in STEM tends to be linked to masculinity, with resulting traditional perceptions that men are more suite
[normal]d to the role. Women are 
[normal]then left in a contradictory situation, judged as being ‘unfeminine’ for having these traits, or unsuitable if judged to not have certain traits.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Several studies have demonstrated unconscious bias against women at interview and in
[normal] the peer review process, whereby people similar to that of the recruiter are employed.
[normal] This can result in a visible lack of women in senior academic positions. Without role models, it is difficult for young women to see academia as a viable option. With 
[normal]few women available to act as mentors, or sit on promotion committees, those who do can become overloaded, which then can inhibit their research achievements. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Students can be biased in their perceptions of leadership, with medical school students of both
[normal] genders reporting that men generally make better leaders. This bias requires challenging within the context of leadership/management/professionalism teaching on image and stereotype.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A fu
[normal]ll-time clinical job is perceived to offer more job security, faster salary progression, no commitment to further examinations, more geographic flexibility and a better work-life balance. Other staff leave for a career in teaching, or industry which pays h
[normal]igher and where promotion prospects are not linked to research income
[normal] or publications,
[normal] which currently is particularly challenging.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Academic 
[normal]STEM loses highly trained and valuable employees who have invested a decade or more in their scientific development. The full range of academic excellence is lost. There are fewer female role models for aspiring clinical academics.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a business 
[normal]case for mixed gender teams.
[normal] Diversity of knowledge and social capital in teams is vital in production of new ideas.
[normal]  
[normal]A lack of women may have a significant impact on the robustness of policy decisions and research innovation
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Overarching:
[normal]7.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universities should establish working groups to continually review staff recruitment, progression, retention and practices that support and e
[normal]nable women’s career progression. Many university departments are working towards or have gained an Athena SWAN award, which supports the advancement of women on 
[normal]science,
[normal] 
[normal]and several have now achieved Silver or Bronze awards.
[normal] An example of good practice i
[normal]s the establishment of the Gender Equality Office within a School of Medicine, Dentistry and Biomedical Sciences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Work-life balance:
[normal]7.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universities should promote a culture of flexible working. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Where possible meetings, networking and other activities shou
[normal]ld be held within core hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Advocate flexible working to suit the individual and the specialty – for example, clinical work may be in a block of several months, or several days a week.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universities should adopt schemes that support female research staf
[normal]f during pregnancy and on returning to work after a period of maternity leave. This should include protected time to concentrate on re-establishing a research portfolio, for example through reduced teaching and administrative workloads. Job applications sh
[normal]ould provide the opportunity for candidates to explain any career breaks.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of confidence:
[normal]7.3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mentoring and networking schemes should be in place for all early career research staff and postdoctoral students.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Promote the visibility of women, 
[normal]and 
[normal]ensure 
[normal]the abilities and achievements of women are highlighted i.e.
[normal] through speakers, presentations and
[normal] media representation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Support and encourage women to consider applying for promotion. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Performance and Development Review should include activity and guidanc
[normal]e for promotion. Routes for promotion should be transparent and accessible. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of opportunities:
[normal]7.4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part-time working should not be a barrier to promotion or opportunities that lead to promotion. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women require 
[normal]development opportunities in areas that lea
[normal]d to promotion, with teaching administrative/pastoral roles distributed equitably. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Trainees require support and guidance as to next steps. Trainees can feel they are undertaking two jobs at once, this can lead to significant stress levels and drop-out. I
[normal]mproved information and communication on internal jobs may help to increase opportunities for the PhD student to remain at the institution. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Career breaks:
[normal]7.5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Career breaks require appropriate management, to reduce impact on research and avoid the attrition 
[normal]of talented individuals. Sufficient time planning the break is required and support to retain links i.e. ‘Keep in Touch’ days or email updates. Funding for staff absence, to avoid overburdening colleagues and to assist the returner i.e. teaching assistance
[normal] or conference attendance, requires consideration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.5.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Identify or create funding streams where the eligibility criteria reflect the protean nature of academia i.e. ac
[normal]ceptance of bids from non-core/
[normal]non-permanent staff members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Role models:
[normal]7.6.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Celebrate successf
[normal]ul women academics. Encourage women to accept offers to speak at conferences and engage with the media, so that women in STEM are more visible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.6.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Have events/online where women graduates can see/hear that it is possible to be a mother and an academic, inclu
[normal]de local case studies, signpost support available before/following maternity leave.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unconscious bias:
[normal]7.7.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universities should put in place positive measures to address the gender imbalance across senior roles, within 
[normal]u
[normal]niversity management and on senior execut
[normal]ive committees.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.7.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recruitment and promotions processes should be transparent
[normal],
[normal] unbiased, and based on merit, regardless of gender, ethnicity or background. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.7.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unconscious bias training for staff conducting annual reviews, or recruitment panel.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Athena SWAN Charter
[normal] recognises and celebrates good employment practice for women working in science, engineering and technology (SET) in higher education, awarding departments with bronze, silver and gold awards. Departments
[normal] within all UK medical and dental schools in the UK are working towards the higher levels of awards. A great deal of good practice has resulted from medical and dental schools working towards or gaining Athena SWAN awards, for example:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Visibility - visibl
[normal]e women and men during open days, speakers for events and interviewers, events specifically to promote the achievements of women academics. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Support - to attend within working hours groups such as a Peer Support Group for Women Returning from Maternity Le
[normal]ave, International Staff Network Group, 
[normal]Women in Science, Engineering and Technology (WiSET), ‘SpringBoard’ workshops
[normal] and formalised mentoring schemes and buddy schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Promotion - workshops to identify and support women ready to apply for promotion, re
[normal]search development support
[normal];
[normal] an opportunities committee, to enhance academic careers for women.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Family-friendly policies - flexible working, career-breaks, return to work schemes following parental or adoption leave, provision of part-time posts with an ho
[normal]norary NHS contract, six month sabbatical for research on return to work, or a dedicated budget to support research whilst women on maternity leave.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]International good practice examples include the focus on institutional change on the National Science Fou
[normal]ndation’s ADVANCE programme in the US
[normal] and the University of California, School of Medicine.
[normal] The Canadian Council of Academies (2010)
[normal] reported on the career trajectory of Canadian women researchers and advocated more flexible models for career progressio
[normal]n.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Research Councils should ensure that consideration of gender issues is included in research funding application forms, as is required for EU grants.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Funding for STEM programs should allow for universities and institutes to focus on institutional change, and encourage outreach and engagement activities.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Advocate that women should be adequately represented on decision-making panels.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Advocate unconscio
[normal]us bias training for those in senior positions.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Advocate that undergraduate teaching should include a discussion on stereotypes, image and bias training to challenge false perceptions and encourage female students to view themselves as potential future leaders. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The MSC and DSC supports the commitment 
[normal]of NIHR and other funding bodies for structured clinical academic training pathways, and urge that this investment be protected. There remains the opportunity to restructure the academic career pathway to avoid the bottleneck at postdoctoral level, and to 
[normal]remove the time-based criteria for fellowships and progression/promotion assessments. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To address specific contractual issues relating to moving between the NHS and an academic career, the Government should review the current admission process to the 
[normal]NHS 
[normal]pension scheme, to allow joiners from clinical and allied health professionals employed by universities. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Family-friendly policies are vital. Childcare should be affordable and high-quality to allow parents to return to work, with adequate provision for a
[normal]ffordable after-school care. Shared maternity/ paternity leave would enable flexibility. Improved support for women returning from career breaks is vital.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]September 2013
